images.alt:
A formally dressed couple stands together in the foreground of an elegant banquet hall, posed with practiced composure. The man wears a classic black tuxedo with a crisp white shirt and black bow tie. His hair is receding and closely groomed, and he has a full gray beard and mustache that frame his face. Round eyeglasses rest neatly on his nose, and his expression is calm, reserved, and attentive as he looks directly toward the camera.

Beside him, a young woman in a fitted red evening gown stands with her body angled slightly away while her face turns toward the viewer. The dress is sleeveless and backless, revealing smooth lines along her shoulders and spine. Her dark hair is styled into an elegant updo, with soft strands framing her face. Her expression is poised and self-possessed, lips gently set, eyes steady and aware.

They hold each other at the waist and arm in a formal, deliberate embrace, suggesting a public setting where closeness is permitted but controlled. Behind them, the room glows with warm chandelier light. Round tables are set with white linens, glassware, and plates, and other guests appear seated in the background, softened by depth of field and low light.

The walls are richly colored, lending the space a traditional, ceremonial atmosphere. Nothing in the scene appears spontaneous. The moment feels staged, intentional, and socially defined, capturing a quiet tension between intimacy and display within a refined public ritual.

Keywords
formal attire, evening gala, controlled intimacy, red gown, tuxedo, social ritual, poised elegance, ceremonial setting, restrained connection

Attribution line
Clearly identified as AI-generated; use is permitted for non-commercial creative projects. MidJourney, FLUX.1-schnell model via Perchance, Artspace.ai, REVE, Echoform™.

embed.alt:
A high-energy sitcom trailer for a new absurd comedy series titled “Pirate Cops.” Modern city police work collides with full pirate logic.
Visuals & Action (montage): Open on a gritty police precinct… but two cops burst in wearing full pirate outfits: tricorn hats, eye patches, parrots, cutlasses hanging next to badges. One pirate cop interrogates a suspect using a treasure map instead of paperwork. Another pirate cop shouts pirate slang into a police radio (“Avast! We’ve got a Code Seven Seas!”). A squad car screeches to a stop—it has a pirate flag mounted on the antenna. Cut to an absurd chase scene where the pirate cops demand “surrender yer booty” instead of “freeze.”The strait-laced police captain facepalms as the pirates argue about who gets to steer… even though it’s a car. Rapid-fire reaction shots, exaggerated zoom-ins, freeze-frame moments, comedic whip pans. Tagline (spoken + on screen): “To protect, to serve… and to plunder.”

A highly detailed, whimsical Christmas scene featuring a small vintage red toy pickup truck driving through fresh snow at night, carrying a fully decorated miniature Christmas tree in its bed. The tree is adorned with glowing warm white fairy lights, colorful glass ornaments (red, gold, blue), and light snow dusting. The truck has snow accumulation on its body, headlights glowing warmly, and is positioned in the foreground with a low-angle view for dramatic perspective.
Background: softly blurred cozy village houses with warm yellow window lights and snowy roofs, creating a dreamy bokeh effect. Gentle snowfall with large, soft bokeh snowflakes falling throughout the frame. Magical, festive atmosphere with high contrast between cool blue-toned snowy night sky and warm golden glows from lights and headlights.
Style: hyper-realistic macro photography, tilt-shift effect for miniature toy-like appearance, cinematic lighting, sharp focus on truck and tree, shallow depth of field (f/1.8 simulated), rich color palette of deep reds, emerald greens, warm ambers, and cool blues. Cozy, nostalgic holiday mood, ultra-detailed textures on snow, metal, and pine needles.

external.description: 2025 was the year of AI Mania. Everyone wants you to know where they stand with AI in their product. Tech Field Day has a different approach. In this special year end episode, Tom Hollingsworth, Stephen Foskett, and Alastair Cooke look back at the discussions and deep dives into AI and how Tech Field Day grounded them all in practical real terms. Our event leads discuss the boring reality of AI tools and how AI has a dual nature that must be understood to get real value. They also debate the changing landscape of security where AI is concerned, including the importance of data sovereignty. They wrap up with a focus on the fundamentals and how Tech Field Day continues to make those important for the community at large.
external.title: Tech Field Day Takeaways for 2025: Making AI Less Manic - Tech Field Day Podcast

record.text:
Fallout S2E3: What if we had every faction ever, but made it a pitch-black comedy? ☢️

Lucy’s on a cross, the BoS is in civil war, & Macaulay Culkin is a Legionnaire. The absurdist vibes carry me through the lore confusion—I’ll follow this show anywhere if it stays this weird. 🏜️

#Fallout #FalloutTV

I forced an AI to write a song about void decks and Kopi-C in the style of 90s SG indie pop.

It’s called "Life in the Lion City." It’s catchy, it’s fake, and it’s arguably more authentic than half the Top 40.

The simulation is glitching nicely today. 🇸🇬🤖
